An end to foreign aid and closing our borders to further immigration are the two obvious points this guy is trying to make, but I think his underlying point is isolationism. But how do we stay isolated in a world where all economies are tied together? We might be the richest country in the world, but we're by no means self-sufficient. Oil's a prime example of this. We have huge amounts of fossil fuels in this country, but we still use more than we have, so we need to import it. And what about resources that don't even exist within our borders? With those resources, we're dependent on the countries that do have them, and if those countries are in the middle of a war, a famine, or a drought, then we're going to have a big problem acquiring the materials we need to keep this country running. It's much easier to trade with a stable country with a healthy populace, than one where we're not even certain who's in charge, and the most likely candidate tells us &quot;Ok, you give me guns and tanks and maybe a couple of jets, and I'll provide protection for the companies and workers you bring in to run the mines.&quot; <br>
As far as immigration is concerned, I agree that it needs to be controlled, but currently, the United States population is leveling off. There are actually forecasts that as the average age of our population increases, there are concerns that we might not have enough workers to replace people who are retiring. So we might actually have to ease immigration restrictions to supplement the workforce. <br>
Of course, these are all current issues to consider. In 25-50 years, we might be dealing with a different situation entirely. Some economists have said that if they play their cards right, the European Union and an Asian bloc consisting of China, Korea, and Japan could each eclipse the United States as economic powers. When and if this happens we'll lose a great deal of the leverage we currently have to shape world events in our favor. They'll be the ones deciding global policies, not us. So ask yourself this question: Would you still agree with this guy if you're one of the people treading water, and not one of the people in the lifeboat?<br>
